@soukainakhalkhouli I think @Dexus is correct you would need to populate any one of these inside tekton build container `${XDG_CONFIG_HOME}/containers/auth.json (usually ~/.config/containers/auth.json), $HOME/.docker/config.json, $HOME/.dockercfg.`  

But tekton can populate `~/.docker/config.json` out of the box from `kubernetes secrets` see : https://tekton.dev/vault/pipelines-v0.16.3/auth/#configuring-authentication-for-docker

I am closing this issue since this looks like more of a tekton issue rather than buildah but please feel free to continue the discussion or re-open if you think something is wrong with buildah here.

@flouthoc ,
Thank you for your response, i'm using tekton for CI/CD  in openshift , i don't have any idea if i should create a secret and apply it after or what exactly i should do .
Regards

@soukainakhalkhouli I think `secrets` and `serviceaccount` are just kubernetes construct so it should be available in openshift as well. So you just need to associate created `serviceaccount` with Tekton's `PipelineRun` or `TaskRun` as stated here: https://tekton.dev/vault/pipelines-v0.16.3/auth/#configuring-basic-auth-authentication-for-docker

**[Not Recommended]** If you don't want to use `secrets` you can just populate `~/.docker/config.json` in your `Tekton Task` manually in `script` section in one of your `steps`. **[Not Recommended]**

Still I think `tekton` or `openshift/tekton` forums  might be the best place to discuss this since they can suggest best way to solve this.
